To All:<br>
Discussed this topic with my father, a Navy Seabee ( Navy engineers) vet that served in Bien Hoa, Saigon, War Zone C and War Zone D area from June 1970-April 1971.  His operations were in support of Vietnamization and 1st Cav operations.  Also discussed this with other Seabees that served in various locations, including all four Corps Tactical Zones.<br><br>
The general opinion and view is that among Navy personnel involved in Vietnamization and construction efforts, drug use was small and nearly non-existant.  Navy NCO's in these units fell hard on users.  In my fathers unit, which spent most of its time in the field, working in remote villages and locations, drug use was nearly non-existant.  The handful of guys that did drugs were Marijuana users and were busted for it by the end of the tour.<br><br>
Through my volunteer work in assisting Nam vets, I been told that drug use effected every unit, but FIELD units suffered the least.  I imagine one needs to stay alert to perform a combat duties.  It has been my impression from talking to vets that support units in larger camps and firebases had the most problems.  Post-war government studies I read and discussed in college point out that Vietnam drug use was no higher than the average drug use in the military outside of Vietnam at the time.  It also stated that Marijuana was the most used drug in Vietnam.  Not having lived through the 60's, my questions to the crowd are:<br>
1.  How different was drug use in the military (Vietnam incuded) from drug use among the civilian population during the 60's ? (The military draws from the population)<br>
2.  Could it be the easy supply of drugs and their cheap price made drug use more widespread? (I hear a guy could buy marijuana made up to look like cigarettes in their original carton for about 2 bucks!) <br><br>
If anything was a problem, in the military as a whole, I would imagine it would be alcohol.  Talk to vets of any war, and you'll hear stories of alcohol abuse, alcohol induced fights, days AWOL or people bearly able to function from hangovers.  I would like to see statistics on alcohol abuse in the miliatary. Arthur Varinelli makes this point clear and I think it needs to be examined.  World War II vets (including my gradfathers) have always said that alcohol was a problem in the military even 50 years ago.   
